english:
  title: A Preface to a Poem Bidding Farewell to Scholar Zhang
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Scholar Zhang of the National Academy departs with Minister Zhu of the Imperial Stables and Minister Duanmu of the Ministry of War, leaving before his two companions after completing his embassy. The Minister of War has composed verses for him and asked me to write a preface. But I am a late scholar dwelling beyond the seas—what wisdom can I offer? This is like asking the deaf what they hear, or commanding the blind to show the way. Yet when Scholar Zhang first arrived, I observed the clarity of his bearing and heard the elegance of his speech, and I harbored a genuine desire for his friendship. How then could I let him depart without a word?

    I have long heard it said that when a scholar of the Way gains understanding within himself, he must necessarily extend it to all things. Master Zhang has thoroughly studied the Classics and Rites and Music, has cultivated Benevolence, Righteousness, Loyalty, and Trustworthiness. His learning has reached illumination, and his conduct has matured to perfection. What he has gained within himself is indeed solid and real. Yet suddenly, before his peers could mark his merit, word of him reached the Son of Heaven's ear, and he received command to serve as envoy thousands of li beyond our borders. Thus begins his influence upon the world.

    To inquire and gather knowledge is the ambassador's foremost duty. Our Eastern realm's sovereigns and ministers serve the greater power with singular sincerity; our customs are plain and simple; our goods are meager; our fields lie barren and thin; our mountains and roads grow steep and narrow. All these things have been thoroughly witnessed and well understood. When one knows of our sincerity, one admires it; when one sees what we cannot accomplish, one forgives it. By praising what is easy and excusing what is difficult, allowing the distant peoples to perpetually receive the benefits flowing eastward—this Master Zhang surely knows how to accomplish.

    When he returns and presents his report, the Sage Son of Heaven, whose vision pierces ten thousand leagues, will surely find accord. Then our Eastern realm shall have lasting benefit. This is the true fruit of learning put into practice, the great work of extending one's influence to all things. Following this principle, even the governance of all under Heaven becomes possible. How could it be only our Eastern realm that would benefit?
  footnotes:
    - The "Eastern realm" (東方) refers to Korea, reflecting the Sino-centric perspective of the era where Korea was positioned to the east of China.
    - The phrase "東漸之澤" (benefits flowing eastward) is a diplomatic courtesy, suggesting Chinese cultural and moral influence benefiting Korea.
    - The reference to "practical learning" (實學) gaining influence over "all things" reflects Neo-Confucian philosophy about how moral self-cultivation extends outward to affect the world.
